public class JsObject
extends Var<JsObject>
implements ObjectLike

An opaque class representing JavaScript objects.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
See Also:
JsGlobal.Number.create(Object), NumberLikes
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be generated into the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on the operations of accessing that kind of class objects. The checkcast operation to the class literal of this interface must be ignored and instanceof to it always true.

Field Detail

constructor

public static final JsFunction.Member<JsObject> constructor

An opaque static field defining a member that is named by the field name without a qualifying member and to access the property of the name on an object.

The constructor property of an object is a reference to the function that was the constructor for that object.

A common use of the constructor property is to determine the type of unknown objects. Given an unknown value, you can use the Js.typeof(Object) operation to determine whether it is a primitive value or an object. If it is an object, you can use the constructor property to determine what type of object it is.

Note, however, that while this technique works for the objects built into core JavaScript, it is not guaranteed to work with host objects such as the window object of client-side JavaScript. The default implementation of the toString() method provides another way to determine the type of an unknown object.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this static field to the identifier of the field name.

hasOwnProperty

public final java.lang.Boolean hasOwnProperty(java.lang.Object propname)

Checks whether the current object instance has a locally defined (non-inherited) property with a specified name.

JavaScript objects may have properties of their own, and they may also inherit properties from their prototype object. This method provides a way to distinguish between inherited properties and non-inherited local properties

Specified by:
hasOwnProperty in interface ObjectLike
Parameters:
propname - A string that contains the name of a property of the current object instance.
Returns:
true if the current object instance has a non-inherited property with the name specified by propname; false if the object does not have a property with the specified name or if it inherits that property from its prototype object.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current array instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

isPrototypeOf

public final java.lang.Boolean isPrototypeOf(java.lang.Object other)

Checks whether the current object instance is the prototype object of a specified object.

This method provides a way to determine if one Object object is the prototype of another

In JavaScript, Object objects inherit properties from their prototype object. The prototype of an Object object is referred to by the prototype property of the constructor function that creates and initializes the object.

Not that, in JS Embed Simulation mode, this method always returns false on a simulated object instance of ObjectLike, unless the instance is converted to a JavaScript object by ObjectLike.var().

Specified by:
isPrototypeOf in interface ObjectLike
Parameters:
other - Any object.
Returns:
true if the current object instance is the prototype of other; false if other is not an Object object or if the current object instance is not the prototype of other.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsObject.Members.constructor, JsClass.prototype
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current array instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.
